1
00:00:03,389 --> 00:00:05,600
Congratulations on the movie.

2
00:00:05,600 --> 00:00:09,090
Why did you want to make a movie with slavery
as a theme?

3
00:00:09,090 --> 00:00:14,200
Did that just come with making a Western in
that period?

4
00:00:14,200 --> 00:00:21,910
I’ve always wanted to explore slavery in
a film before.

5
00:00:21,910 --> 00:00:26,660
But I think actually my real reason – I’ve
always wanted to explore slavery but I guess

6
00:00:26,660 --> 00:00:34,210
the reason that actually made me put pen to
paper was to give black American males a Western

7
00:00:34,210 --> 00:00:35,210
hero.

8
00:00:35,210 --> 00:00:40,530
Give them a cool folkloric hero that could
actually be empowering and actually pay back

9
00:00:40,530 --> 00:00:41,530
blood for blood.

10
00:00:41,530 --> 00:00:43,899
And that’s the revenge bit.

11
00:00:43,899 --> 00:00:46,600
Is that essential for making a hero?

12
00:00:46,600 --> 00:00:59,160
Well in this story – well in the case of
laying waste to a genocidal white racist class

13
00:00:59,160 --> 00:01:01,899
in the institution of slavery, yes, that would
be the reason to do it.

14
00:01:01,899 --> 00:01:06,610
As opposed to just a historical story where
this happens and this happens and this happens

15
00:01:06,610 --> 00:01:08,740
and this happens and that happens.

16
00:01:08,740 --> 00:01:11,730
So you can’t be surprised by the controversy
that’s come along with it?

17
00:01:11,730 --> 00:01:14,790
Well you can’t - I don’t think you can
actually make a movie about slavery in America

18
00:01:14,790 --> 00:01:16,070
that is not going to be controversial.

19
00:01:16,070 --> 00:01:19,610
Are you very disappointed by some of the reactions,
Spike Lee especially?

20
00:01:19,610 --> 00:01:24,070
I couldn’t be happier with the reaction
to this movie, it’s been fantastic.

21
00:01:24,070 --> 00:01:27,479
Its good publicity I suppose but I mean-
No no no it’s creating a nice debate, even

22
00:01:27,479 --> 00:01:32,590
the people who don’t like the film.

23
00:01:32,590 --> 00:01:38,630
I am responsible for people talking about
slavery in America in a way that they have

24
00:01:38,630 --> 00:01:40,930
not in thirty years.

25
00:01:40,930 --> 00:01:46,310
But you must care very deeply that this doesn’t
become a film that stands out from the rest

26
00:01:46,310 --> 00:01:50,810
of your body of work, as one that is trashed
by more people or anything like that.

27
00:01:50,810 --> 00:01:54,039
It’s not trashed by more people.

28
00:01:54,039 --> 00:01:55,440
What you are saying is not correct.

29
00:01:55,440 --> 00:01:58,290
No I’m not saying it is, I’m saying are
you concerned?

30
00:01:58,290 --> 00:02:02,210
No no no I’m not talking about the movie
right now, you’re talking about, you know,

31
00:02:02,210 --> 00:02:07,289
there is actually a dialogue going on about
slavery right now that has not been happening

32
00:02:07,289 --> 00:02:08,289
at all.

33
00:02:08,289 --> 00:02:12,200
It’s a subject people are afraid to talk
about and now because of this movie people

34
00:02:12,200 --> 00:02:14,130
aren’t afraid to talk about it.

35
00:02:14,130 --> 00:02:16,290
People are talking about it.

36
00:02:16,290 --> 00:02:20,190
Somebody likes the movie and they write a
review on this – especially in a world right

37
00:02:20,190 --> 00:02:24,640
now where you actually have the internet where
actually anybody can actually now speak publicly,

38
00:02:24,640 --> 00:02:25,750
which was not the case before.

39
00:02:25,750 --> 00:02:29,230
So now somebody actually writes a review for
the movie and they like it.

40
00:02:29,230 --> 00:02:33,250
You read the comment section and some people
who don’t like it attack them and say their

41
00:02:33,250 --> 00:02:34,250
saying.

42
00:02:34,250 --> 00:02:36,510
Somebody who doesn’t like the movie writes
a blog about it and the people who like the

43
00:02:36,510 --> 00:02:38,980
movie hold them to task in the comment section.

44
00:02:38,980 --> 00:02:41,110
That’s an actual dialogue.

45
00:02:41,110 --> 00:02:44,420
Let me ask you about violence.

46
00:02:44,420 --> 00:02:48,670
You said, everyone knows you make violent
movies, you like violent movies.

47
00:02:48,670 --> 00:02:52,090
Why do you like making violent movies?

48
00:02:52,090 --> 00:03:00,159
I don’t know, it’s like asking Judd Apatow
why do you like making comedies?

49
00:03:00,159 --> 00:03:04,340
You just get a kick out of it or you just
enjoy it or?

50
00:03:04,340 --> 00:03:09,760
It’s a - I think it’s good cinema.

51
00:03:09,760 --> 00:03:13,379
I consider it good cinema.

52
00:03:13,379 --> 00:03:17,670
You sit there in a movie theatre when these
cathartic violent scenes happen and I’m

53
00:03:17,670 --> 00:03:19,769
talking about cathartic violent scenes, I’m
not talking about…

54
00:03:19,769 --> 00:03:22,250
There’s two types of violence in this movie.

55
00:03:22,250 --> 00:03:29,900
There’s the brutality of the violence in
the day put upon the slaves

56
00:03:29,900 --> 00:03:34,150
The rape of the women and the-
I don’t think there’s any rape going on

57
00:03:34,150 --> 00:03:35,299
in the movie.

58
00:03:35,299 --> 00:03:38,060
But there’s brutality to the slaves.

59
00:03:38,060 --> 00:03:42,739
That hasn’t been dealt with in America to
the extent that I deal with it and I’m showing

60
00:03:42,739 --> 00:03:46,520
you that there was two holocausts in America,
this is one of them.

61
00:03:46,520 --> 00:03:52,500
We’ve dealt with the Indian holocaust, the
holocaust of the American-Indian in America.

62
00:03:52,500 --> 00:03:58,500
But we haven’t been dealing with the holocaustic
aspects, the Auschwitzian aspects of the slave

63
00:03:58,500 --> 00:03:59,610
trade in America.

64
00:03:59,610 --> 00:04:01,110
My movie deals with that.

65
00:04:01,110 --> 00:04:05,689
Then there’s the cathartic violence of Django
paying back blood for blood.

66
00:04:05,689 --> 00:04:09,680
And is that why you think people like watching
violent movies?

67
00:04:09,680 --> 00:04:16,430
People who are not violent people or twisted
people in any way, but why it’s okay to

68
00:04:16,430 --> 00:04:18,060
go into a movie and enjoy the violence?

69
00:04:18,060 --> 00:04:19,810
Yeah, well it’s a movie.

70
00:04:19,810 --> 00:04:20,860
It’s a fantasy.

71
00:04:20,860 --> 00:04:22,501
It’s a fantasy, it’s not real life.

72
00:04:22,501 --> 00:04:28,540
It’s a fantasy, you go and you watch a Kung-Fu
movie and one guy takes on a hundred people

73
00:04:28,540 --> 00:04:29,540
in a restaurant.

74
00:04:29,540 --> 00:04:30,540
That’s fun.

75
00:04:30,540 --> 00:04:35,250
But why are you so sure there’s no link
between enjoying movie violence and enjoying

76
00:04:35,250 --> 00:04:36,250
real violence?

77
00:04:36,250 --> 00:04:41,410
Well I’m going to tell you why I’m so
sure – Do not ask me a question like that.

78
00:04:41,410 --> 00:04:42,410
I’m not biting.

79
00:04:42,410 --> 00:04:43,410
I refuse your question.

80
00:04:43,410 --> 00:04:44,410
Why?

81
00:04:44,410 --> 00:04:46,480
Because I refuse your question and I’m not
your slave and you’re not my master.

82
00:04:46,480 --> 00:04:48,120
You can’t make me dance to your tune.

83
00:04:48,120 --> 00:04:49,120
I’m not a monkey.

84
00:04:49,120 --> 00:04:52,650
I can’t make you answer anything I’m just
asking you interesting questions.

85
00:04:52,650 --> 00:04:53,710
And I’m saying I refuse.

86
00:04:53,710 --> 00:04:57,430
I was just asking you why, that’s fine.

87
00:04:57,430 --> 00:05:01,970
See Jamie Foxx has said “We can’t turn
our back and say that violence in films-“

88
00:05:01,970 --> 00:05:05,950
Well then you should talk to Jamie Foxx about
that.

89
00:05:05,950 --> 00:05:07,780
And I think he’s actually here so you can.

90
00:05:07,780 --> 00:05:12,210
I’d love to, but it’s interesting that
you have a different view and I’m just trying

91
00:05:12,210 --> 00:05:13,210
to explore that.

92
00:05:13,210 --> 00:05:14,210
And I don’t want to.

93
00:05:14,210 --> 00:05:17,300
Because I’m here to sell my movie.

94
00:05:17,300 --> 00:05:19,320
This is a commercial for the movie make no
mistake.

95
00:05:19,320 --> 00:05:22,680
So you don’t want to talk about anything
serious?

96
00:05:22,680 --> 00:05:24,590
I don’t want to talk about what you want
to talk about.

97
00:05:24,590 --> 00:05:29,020
I don’t want to talk about the implications
of violence.

98
00:05:29,020 --> 00:05:31,190
The reason I don’t want to talk about it;
because I’ve said everything I’ve had

99
00:05:31,190 --> 00:05:32,470
to say about it.

100
00:05:32,470 --> 00:05:36,600
If anyone cares what I have to say about it,
they can google me and they can look for twenty

101
00:05:36,600 --> 00:05:38,370
years what I have to say about it.

102
00:05:38,370 --> 00:05:42,590
I haven’t changed my opinion one iota.

103
00:05:42,590 --> 00:05:45,370
No but you haven’t fleshed it out.

104
00:05:45,370 --> 00:05:48,090
It’s not my job to flesh it out.

105
00:05:48,090 --> 00:05:50,050
No it’s my job to try and ask you to.

106
00:05:50,050 --> 00:05:52,060
And I’m shutting your butt down.

107
00:05:52,060 --> 00:05:54,340
That’s entirely your right.

108
00:05:54,340 --> 00:05:56,620
This is a commercial for my movie.

109
00:05:56,620 --> 00:06:02,150
I know, but it’s my job to try and export
some serious themes as well

110
00:06:02,150 --> 00:06:05,710
I invite you to explore some serious themes,
but not the themes I’ve already been on

111
00:06:05,710 --> 00:06:06,910
the record for talking about.

112
00:06:06,910 --> 00:06:12,530
But violence is such a big part of all of
your movies and it’s an enjoyable part of

113
00:06:12,530 --> 00:06:16,250
your movies for so many people and that’s
why I’m talking about this.

114
00:06:16,250 --> 00:06:18,240
It’s a very sensitive time at the moment.

115
00:06:18,240 --> 00:06:23,030
The Vice-President is talking to people in
the movie industry today about violence and

116
00:06:23,030 --> 00:06:25,590
response-
And you know where I stand on it.

117
00:06:25,590 --> 00:06:26,590
Which is that there is no relationship.

118
00:06:26,590 --> 00:06:27,590
Yes.

119
00:06:27,590 --> 00:06:29,790
But you haven’t said why you think there
is no relationship.

120
00:06:29,790 --> 00:06:32,290
It’s none of your damn business what I think
about that.

121
00:06:32,290 --> 00:06:37,650
Well, it’s my job to ask you why-
And I’m saying no.

122
00:06:37,650 --> 00:06:39,740
And I am shutting you down.

123
00:06:39,740 --> 00:06:45,120
But you have a responsibility as a film maker
surely to explain a little bit about what

124
00:06:45,120 --> 00:06:46,120
you’re doing?

125
00:06:46,120 --> 00:06:48,630
No I don’t have any responsibility to you
to explain anything I don’t want to.

126
00:06:48,630 --> 00:06:51,660
Not to me, but to your viewers, to you fans.

127
00:06:51,660 --> 00:06:54,520
To people who care about what it is that you’re
doing.

128
00:06:54,520 --> 00:06:57,440
They know where I’m coming from.

129
00:06:57,440 --> 00:06:59,240
And I have explained it.

130
00:06:59,240 --> 00:07:02,280
And I have explained even what you’re talking
about it, I’m just not giving it to you.

131
00:07:02,280 --> 00:07:03,280
Why?

132
00:07:03,280 --> 00:07:05,630
Because I don’t want to, because I’ve
done it already.

133
00:07:05,630 --> 00:07:08,710
I have explained this many times in the last
twenty years.

134
00:07:08,710 --> 00:07:13,090
I just refuse to repeat myself over and over
again because you want me to.

135
00:07:13,090 --> 00:07:15,300
For you and your show and your ratings.

136
00:07:15,300 --> 00:07:16,660
It’s not about our ratings.

137
00:07:16,660 --> 00:07:23,250
No it is, it’s about you want me to say
it for you, for your show, this show right

138
00:07:23,250 --> 00:07:24,250
here right now.

139
00:07:24,250 --> 00:07:27,840
Well look, this is a news program not a film
program so we export serious themes, that’s

140
00:07:27,840 --> 00:07:29,060
the difference.

141
00:07:29,060 --> 00:07:32,590
But you want me to do what I’ve already
done before and I am refusing.

142
00:07:32,590 --> 00:07:34,580
Fine, that’s your right.

143
00:07:34,580 --> 00:07:38,800
Let me also ask you: You said in a playboy
interview recently that you thought movie

144
00:07:38,800 --> 00:07:42,130
directors didn’t get better as they get
older.

145
00:07:42,130 --> 00:07:45,120
Are you getting better as you get older or
worse?

146
00:07:45,120 --> 00:07:48,630
They don’t get better when they get old.

147
00:07:48,630 --> 00:07:51,180
I think I’m still in the sweet spot.

148
00:07:51,180 --> 00:07:52,180
Well I hope.

149
00:07:52,180 --> 00:07:53,520
That’s up for everyone to decide.

150
00:07:53,520 --> 00:07:54,520
Am I?

151
00:07:54,520 --> 00:07:57,190
I enjoy your movies.

152
00:07:57,190 --> 00:07:59,030
You probably wouldn’t believe that.

153
00:07:59,030 --> 00:08:06,090
I was just wondering what you think is left,
you’ve done several big movies.

154
00:08:06,090 --> 00:08:08,250
Let me answer your question about that.

155
00:08:08,250 --> 00:08:16,500
I just feel like filmmaking directors are
like boxers.

156
00:08:16,500 --> 00:08:18,590
They have their time.

157
00:08:18,590 --> 00:08:19,590
They have their time.

158
00:08:19,590 --> 00:08:22,770
Hopefully, I’m on the right side of my time.

159
00:08:22,770 --> 00:08:25,390
But at a certain point a boxer loses.

160
00:08:25,390 --> 00:08:28,050
And it’s all about knowing when?

161
00:08:28,050 --> 00:08:31,950
It’s all about knowing when to hang up the
gloves or in my case I guess the megaphone.

162
00:08:31,950 --> 00:08:34,000
Quentin Tarantino, thank you very much.

163
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:34,689
Thank you.

